snippet.textDisplay:
So I went to a party with members of the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) at my university a while back, shortly after Cyber Truck was unveiled and we had a discussion on the aerodynamics and flow separation issues that would result from the, relatively speaking, sharp bends and angles on the body. Do you guys plan on trying to wind tunnel test it to see if the body design has any improvement over a traditional truck body with respect to aerodynamics? I'm just not certain that this is the most efficient design possible, which can make a bigger difference with electric vehicles and the relative inconvenience of recharging them currently.

Oh and you compared Nm to ft-lbs as if they were a 1:1 conversion which kinda was misleading since 1 Nm is less than 1 ft-lb, but I understand that it is incredibly easy to mix unit systems thanks to the US not fully adopting the metric system. Overall the project looks really good and the massive amount of work and dedication really shows on this project.

snippet.textDisplay: I've had my Raycon E25s for a couple months now and honestly they're not that good. Pairing is not seamless, in fact they have quite a bit of trouble with it. The audio tends to cut back and forth between the left and right earbuds. After about a month the battery only lasts a couple hours before needing to be recharged. The charging case is poorly made and the matte finish wears off fast with regular use. Even after using the best fit of the gel tips provided, the left earbud still managed to fall out of my ear and into sink (down the drain) while I was washing my hands. They are not worth the $80 I paid for mine.
